00:48:05.210 --> 00:48:07.890
to non-lucid dreaming.

00:48:07.890 --> 00:48:11.050
I mean, I know that people
anecdotally often report

00:48:11.050 --> 00:48:12.830
that well, the
lucid dream state is

00:48:12.830 --> 00:48:16.030
very-- there's the kind of
excitation in the state.

00:48:16.030 --> 00:48:19.380
And you know, your
alertness is ramped up.

00:48:19.380 --> 00:48:20.930
And people have
sometimes said, so I

00:48:20.930 --> 00:48:23.450
feel like I didn't have
as restful a sleep.

00:48:23.450 --> 00:48:25.980
I think my own
sense-- again, I don't

00:48:25.980 --> 00:48:27.480
think this is based
on evidence yet,

00:48:27.480 --> 00:48:29.040
but this is my own
kind of sense--

00:48:29.040 --> 00:48:31.170
is that it really
depends a lot on how

00:48:31.170 --> 00:48:32.820
you approach lucid dreaming.

00:48:32.820 --> 00:48:35.240
I think especially
if it's approached

00:48:35.240 --> 00:48:37.770
in a contemplative
way, say in the context

00:48:37.770 --> 00:48:40.500
of what in Tibetan Buddhism
would be called dream yoga,

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:44.000
or in the context of
Hindu yoga would be called

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:46.340
sleep yoga, where
it's an opportunity

00:48:46.340 --> 00:48:49.320
to be aware of the mind
and the creative power

00:48:49.320 --> 00:48:52.540
of the mind without
attachment, just

00:48:52.540 --> 00:48:57.130
a kind of restful
observation, then my suspicion

00:48:57.130 --> 00:49:02.480
would be that that would
have effects on how restful

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:04.040
or not it felt.

00:49:04.040 --> 00:49:05.700
That's my own sense.

00:49:05.700 --> 00:49:08.970
I'm not a really-- I can't
lucid dream on demand.

00:49:08.970 --> 00:49:11.580
So I can't test it
myself experientially.

00:49:11.580 --> 00:49:15.260
I mean, I lucid dream
reasonably frequently

00:49:15.260 --> 00:49:21.650
with a certain amount of
ability to test certain things.

00:49:21.650 --> 00:49:26.380
And my sense is that if
it's approached that way,

00:49:26.380 --> 00:49:30.200
then I don't wake up in a
kind of excited, agitated way.

00:49:30.200 --> 00:49:35.460
I wake up in a more balanced
way, I suppose you could say.

00:49:35.460 --> 00:49:39.530
AUDIENCE: I'm curious if there's
many fMRI studies on either

00:49:39.530 --> 00:49:42.780
those that are kind of
considered enlightened, where

00:49:42.780 --> 00:49:45.680
they talk about the self
as no longer a process,

00:49:45.680 --> 00:49:47.070
like maharishi.

00:49:47.070 --> 00:49:50.390
You're familiar with that
where people that identify

00:49:50.390 --> 00:49:52.110
with the capital S self.

00:49:52.110 --> 00:49:54.690
Or there's also
psychotropic substances,

00:49:54.690 --> 00:49:57.550
like salvia divinorum,
where people

00:49:57.550 --> 00:50:00.590
report that they are no longer
at all identified with self.

00:50:00.590 --> 00:50:03.550
And they are an object
in that experience.

00:50:03.550 --> 00:50:05.752
And that being an
illegal substance,

00:50:05.752 --> 00:50:08.540
I'm just curious if that's
now hitting the radar.

00:50:08.540 --> 00:50:10.560
I know in "Search
Inside Yourself"

00:50:10.560 --> 00:50:14.040
they did say some uses of
LSD were being brought back

00:50:14.040 --> 00:50:15.050
into studies.

00:50:15.050 --> 00:50:18.204
So just curious if one people
that sort of claim they

00:50:18.204 --> 00:50:19.870
have this constant
awareness-- you know,

00:50:19.870 --> 00:50:22.020
the Tibetans talk about
in "Waking, Dreaming,

00:50:22.020 --> 00:50:24.022
Sleeping," there is a
very high level of state,

00:50:24.022 --> 00:50:25.480
where you're just
constantly aware.

00:50:25.480 --> 00:50:26.960
Has anybody like
that been studied?

00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:28.840
And then second, are
they studying folks

00:50:28.840 --> 00:50:31.290
under the influence of
drugs that can actually

00:50:31.290 --> 00:50:34.910
sort of create that sense
for limited periods of time?

00:50:34.910 --> 00:50:38.090
EVAN THOMPSON: Data on
those kinds of experiences

00:50:38.090 --> 00:50:39.950
is very, very minimal
at this point.

00:50:39.950 --> 00:50:44.461
I mean, LSD research is just
kind of getting going again.

00:50:47.680 --> 00:50:52.040
Even the research on meditation
is very much still limited

00:50:52.040 --> 00:50:54.824
by all sorts of things.

00:50:54.824 --> 00:50:56.740
And there's always the
question of exactly how

00:50:56.740 --> 00:51:00.580
to interpret reports like a
continuous constant awareness.

00:51:00.580 --> 00:51:04.494
Certain traditions frame
things in terms of that.

00:51:04.494 --> 00:51:06.160
So then there's the
likelihood that that

00:51:06.160 --> 00:51:08.970
would be a report
that some individual

00:51:08.970 --> 00:51:13.130
from a particular practice
tradition might make.

00:51:13.130 --> 00:51:17.860
I myself stay away from
the enlightenment word.

00:51:17.860 --> 00:51:21.670
I think it's not
helpful to think

00:51:21.670 --> 00:51:24.460
of enlightenment as there's
a state that's enlightenment.

00:51:24.460 --> 00:51:29.260
And we can study it in Brazilian
shamans and in Tibet meditators

00:51:29.260 --> 00:51:31.110
and in secular Westerners.

00:51:31.110 --> 00:51:33.039
I think enlightenment,
especially

00:51:33.039 --> 00:51:35.080
from a history of religion,
history of philosophy

00:51:35.080 --> 00:51:38.210
perspective, is a concept that's
used in different traditions

00:51:38.210 --> 00:51:38.960
in different ways.

00:51:38.960 --> 00:51:40.680
And it means different things.

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:42.550
And it's always in
some ways contested.

00:51:42.550 --> 00:51:47.950
Different individuals make
claims for certain individuals

00:51:47.950 --> 00:51:48.930
having attainments.

00:51:48.930 --> 00:51:52.810
They function rhetorically
to legitimize in certain ways

00:51:52.810 --> 00:51:53.870
in various communities.

00:51:53.870 --> 00:51:56.940
So in that sense
I'm kind of-- it's

00:51:56.940 --> 00:51:59.850
not that I don't think there
are states of profound awakening

00:51:59.850 --> 00:52:01.090
and realization.

00:52:01.090 --> 00:52:04.890
But kind of reifying them into
the category enlightenment,

00:52:04.890 --> 00:52:05.994
I'm very wary of.

00:52:05.994 --> 00:52:08.285
AUDIENCE: You mean like
non-dual awareness [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:08.285 --> 00:52:09.160
EVAN THOMPSON: Mm hm.

00:52:09.160 --> 00:52:11.420
But even there, like,
what exactly-- yeah.

00:52:11.420 --> 00:52:13.008
What exactly does non-dual mean?

00:52:15.990 --> 00:52:17.700
That's something
that if you look

00:52:17.700 --> 00:52:20.190
at the history of
Buddhism, for example,

00:52:20.190 --> 00:52:23.090
there's big disputes and debates
in Chinese Zen and Tibetan

00:52:23.090 --> 00:52:23.980
Buddhism.

00:52:23.980 --> 00:52:26.630
A lot rides on the debates
in terms of philosophy,

00:52:26.630 --> 00:52:28.200
prestige, lineage.

00:52:28.200 --> 00:52:31.655
So you know, I think
one of the dangers

00:52:31.655 --> 00:52:33.280
of the scientific
research is thinking,

00:52:33.280 --> 00:52:34.560
oh, there is this thing
non-dual awareness.

00:52:34.560 --> 00:52:36.518
And now we're going to
image it in the scanner.

00:52:36.518 --> 00:52:39.610
And I really think that that's
a kind of reification of a much

00:52:39.610 --> 00:52:41.170
more complex phenomenon.

00:52:41.170 --> 00:52:45.100
AUDIENCE: So you talked about
the sense of self as a process,

00:52:45.100 --> 00:52:48.020
as enactment or construction
of consciousness.

00:52:48.020 --> 00:52:50.760
I'm curious how
far you would you

00:52:50.760 --> 00:52:53.940
take it in correlation
with some Buddhist thought?

00:52:53.940 --> 00:52:58.700
I mean, one could say
everything is a construction.

00:52:58.700 --> 00:53:02.220
Can we definitively say you
as a philosopher, a scientist,

00:53:02.220 --> 00:53:06.600
that there exists
anything in itself

00:53:06.600 --> 00:53:09.580
with a non-constructed
existence?

00:53:09.580 --> 00:53:10.690
So how far do you take it?

00:53:10.690 --> 00:53:11.650
EVAN THOMPSON: Yeah.

00:53:11.650 --> 00:53:15.660
Well, I think
everything is processed.

00:53:15.660 --> 00:53:18.719
And everything is under constant
construction as a process.

00:53:18.719 --> 00:53:20.010
That would be the short answer.

00:53:20.010 --> 00:53:24.760
I think not everything
involves the kind

00:53:24.760 --> 00:53:27.830
of structured self-experience
that I've been talking about.

00:53:27.830 --> 00:53:32.105
That's a particular way that
things can get constructed,

00:53:32.105 --> 00:53:34.230
especially when we're
dealing with social cognition

00:53:34.230 --> 00:53:34.771
and language.

00:53:34.771 --> 00:53:36.760
That's very much
how we human beings

00:53:36.760 --> 00:53:38.270
construct ourselves socially.

00:53:38.270 --> 00:53:39.978
And it's an interesting
question how much

00:53:39.978 --> 00:53:42.350
other forms of animal
life do things similarly

00:53:42.350 --> 00:53:43.800
or differently.

00:53:43.800 --> 00:53:47.170
But in terms of a broader kind
of metaphysical perspective

00:53:47.170 --> 00:53:50.880
as a philosopher, I mean, I'm
very much of an orientation

00:53:50.880 --> 00:53:53.330
that sees things as
a kind of process

00:53:53.330 --> 00:53:56.699
all the way down, and under
constant construction,

00:53:56.699 --> 00:53:58.990
or configuring and reconfiguring
all the way up and all

00:53:58.990 --> 00:54:00.190
the way down.

00:54:00.190 --> 00:54:02.140
AUDIENCE: We have
some questions online.

00:54:02.140 --> 00:54:04.530
So in the interest
of time, I'll just

00:54:04.530 --> 00:54:07.510
ask the one that
got the most vote.

00:54:07.510 --> 00:54:09.570
So the question is,
what is the evidence

00:54:09.570 --> 00:54:12.000
for a consistent
long-term meditation

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:15.230
practice enhancing and
improving the neural pathways

00:54:15.230 --> 00:54:15.890
in the brain?

00:54:17.530 --> 00:54:19.030
EVAN THOMPSON: I
would actually say,

00:54:19.030 --> 00:54:24.780
to be quite frank, the evidence
right now is still very,

00:54:24.780 --> 00:54:29.020
very-- I was going to say thin.

00:54:29.020 --> 00:54:31.700
But that's kind of a
prejudicial way of putting it.

00:54:32.340 --> 00:54:34.400
I think that we're not
in a situation where

00:54:34.400 --> 00:54:41.400
we can say there is strong
evidence that the brain is

00:54:41.400 --> 00:54:46.160
altered in ways that
are positive as a result

00:54:46.160 --> 00:54:47.130
of meditation practice.

00:54:47.130 --> 00:54:48.350
I think we have
reason to believe

00:54:48.350 --> 00:54:49.516
that that might be the case.

00:54:49.516 --> 00:54:51.470
But in terms of actual
evidence, the kinds

00:54:51.470 --> 00:54:53.600
of studies with
the right controls,

00:54:53.600 --> 00:54:56.830
I still think that that
evidence is not quite there yet,

00:54:56.830 --> 00:55:00.030
despite all the hype
that it's there.

00:55:00.030 --> 00:55:01.630
So I think scientific
honesty really

00:55:01.630 --> 00:55:04.550
requires us saying that
could be something that

00:55:04.550 --> 00:55:06.799
is borne out by future study.

00:55:06.799 --> 00:55:08.840
And we may have good
reasons to hypothesize that.

00:55:08.840 --> 00:55:12.110
But in terms of actual
evidence, that's

00:55:12.110 --> 00:55:13.730
really not on the table yet.

00:55:13.730 --> 00:55:16.670
The one other thing
I would say is

00:55:16.670 --> 00:55:20.220
that we read a lot,
meditation changes the brain.

00:55:20.220 --> 00:55:22.720
But everything changes
the brain all the time.

00:55:22.720 --> 00:55:24.710
If I take a sip of
water from the bottle,

00:55:24.710 --> 00:55:26.270
my brain is changed.

00:55:26.270 --> 00:55:28.806
So the idea that there's
something special

00:55:28.806 --> 00:55:30.180
about meditation
cause it changes

00:55:30.180 --> 00:55:31.781
the brain, that's really hype.

00:55:31.781 --> 00:55:33.530
Everything all the
time changes the brain.

00:55:33.530 --> 00:55:34.370
And the question is, OK.

00:55:34.370 --> 00:55:35.734
So how does it change the brain?

00:55:35.734 --> 00:55:36.650
Under what conditions?

00:55:36.650 --> 00:55:37.930
In what context?

00:55:37.930 --> 00:55:40.490
And the danger is that we
focus just on the brain.

00:55:40.490 --> 00:55:42.030
Because it's about community.

00:55:42.030 --> 00:55:43.610
It's about culture.

00:55:43.610 --> 00:55:45.430
It's about history.

00:55:45.430 --> 00:55:48.990
And that is as much,
if not more, important

00:55:48.990 --> 00:55:51.160
than just looking
at what the brain is

00:55:51.160 --> 00:55:52.966
as we can currently measure it.

00:55:52.966 --> 00:55:53.840
That's a long answer.

00:55:53.840 --> 00:55:57.530
But that's my position.

00:55:57.530 --> 00:55:59.030
AUDIENCE: So I just
want to hear you

00:55:59.030 --> 00:56:04.060
speak to the concept of
neural diversity in continuum.

00:56:04.060 --> 00:56:06.620
We have a lot of
conversations in society

00:56:06.620 --> 00:56:09.620
now about autism,
Asperger's, things like that.

00:56:09.620 --> 00:56:13.504
How does the sense of self
kind of intersect with that?

00:56:13.504 --> 00:56:15.420
EVAN THOMPSON: I mean,
I think that's a really

00:56:15.420 --> 00:56:18.340
huge and important question.

00:56:18.340 --> 00:56:22.770
And I'm not by any means-- I
don't really have the expertise

00:56:22.770 --> 00:56:25.510
to address it in a full way.

00:56:25.510 --> 00:56:30.640
But I think that any account
of self-experience has to take

00:56:30.640 --> 00:56:34.720
account of the various kinds
of different developmental

00:56:34.720 --> 00:56:41.296
trajectories that appear
with autism or Asperger's.

00:56:41.296 --> 00:56:42.670
And again, there
all I would want

00:56:42.670 --> 00:56:47.310
to say is that we shouldn't
leap to think that it's all just

00:56:47.310 --> 00:56:50.080
a matter of the brain
being different.

00:56:50.080 --> 00:56:52.410
That again, a lot
of what happens

00:56:52.410 --> 00:56:55.780
in culture and society and
social practices, I think,

00:56:55.780 --> 00:56:57.390
is really important there.

00:56:57.390 --> 00:57:01.580
And wider somatic perspectives
than just the brain.

00:57:01.580 --> 00:57:04.830
But it's definitely an
aspect of self-experience

00:57:04.830 --> 00:57:07.559
that would need to be part
of a more complete account.

00:57:07.559 --> 00:57:09.350
It's not something I
talk about in my book.

00:57:09.350 --> 00:57:13.020
I don't really have the
expertise to address it.

00:57:13.020 --> 00:57:14.840
Yeah.

00:57:14.840 --> 00:57:15.640
Yeah.

00:57:15.640 --> 00:57:17.030
AUDIENCE: I've got a question.

00:57:17.030 --> 00:57:21.760
After years of research and work
in this field, and by the way,

00:57:21.760 --> 00:57:23.980
thank you for all your ideas.

00:57:23.980 --> 00:57:27.170
How has that helped
you in your life?

00:57:27.170 --> 00:57:31.610
Or did it help to make sense
of the world of your existence,

00:57:31.610 --> 00:57:32.714
like, for you personally?

00:57:35.397 --> 00:57:37.980
EVAN THOMPSON: I'm almost at a
loss as to know where to begin,

00:57:37.980 --> 00:57:39.671
because in so many
different ways.

00:57:42.830 --> 00:57:46.400
So I mean, I'm a
philosopher by training.

00:57:46.400 --> 00:57:49.150
So what's very important
to me in thinking

00:57:49.150 --> 00:57:52.320
about philosophical questions
of the meaning of life,

00:57:52.320 --> 00:57:55.330
or what happens at
death, or how should

00:57:55.330 --> 00:57:58.360
we as finite limited
creatures face something

00:57:58.360 --> 00:58:00.740
like the inevitability
of death, that

00:58:00.740 --> 00:58:03.130
the contemplative
perspectives on the one hand

00:58:03.130 --> 00:58:07.400
bring a depth of mental
training and practice to that.

00:58:07.400 --> 00:58:11.440
But having the scientific
perspective complement

00:58:11.440 --> 00:58:16.600
that, where we can have the
scientific knowledge together

00:58:16.600 --> 00:58:19.262
with the contemplative
knowledge inform-- I'll

00:58:19.262 --> 00:58:21.470
just take death as an example,
because it's something

00:58:21.470 --> 00:58:25.250
that I've been thinking a
fair amount about recently.

00:58:25.250 --> 00:58:27.300
You know, we're a culture
that kind of hides

00:58:27.300 --> 00:58:29.040
from and runs away from death.

00:58:29.040 --> 00:58:32.850
So having the kind of rich,
contemplative perspective

00:58:32.850 --> 00:58:36.800
informed by rich philosophies
with deep scientific knowledge,

00:58:36.800 --> 00:58:39.060
I think really has
made a difference to me

00:58:39.060 --> 00:58:41.470
in how I think about
how I would want

00:58:41.470 --> 00:58:44.130
to die, how I want to live
given that I'm going to die,

00:58:44.130 --> 00:58:46.380
what hospice care could
be like if we really

00:58:46.380 --> 00:58:48.760
had that kind of sensibility.

00:58:48.760 --> 00:58:50.755
So those are just
some of the things

00:58:50.755 --> 00:58:52.130
that kind of come
out immediately

00:58:52.130 --> 00:58:54.180
in response to your question.

00:58:54.180 --> 00:58:56.430
AUDIENCE: You mentioned it
just now in death, and also

00:58:56.430 --> 00:58:58.730
previously in your talk
around near-death experiences.

00:58:58.730 --> 00:59:02.560
I was curious to hear
your kind of perspective

00:59:02.560 --> 00:59:05.800
on near-death experiences,
and how it impacts your work.

00:59:05.800 --> 00:59:07.670
EVAN THOMPSON: Yeah.

00:59:07.670 --> 00:59:11.820
So I think near-death
experiences

00:59:11.820 --> 00:59:17.215
are experiences that
have been reported,

00:59:17.215 --> 00:59:19.840
or things we can call near-death
experiences have been reported

00:59:19.840 --> 00:59:24.140
in many different cultures, many
different historical periods.

00:59:24.140 --> 00:59:26.940
There's also ways
in which they're

00:59:26.940 --> 00:59:29.230
unique and new because of
our medical resuscitation

00:59:29.230 --> 00:59:31.230
techniques.

00:59:31.230 --> 00:59:33.830
It's unquestionably the
case, it seems to me,

00:59:33.830 --> 00:59:36.940
that these experiences are
genuine experiences that have

00:59:36.940 --> 00:59:40.770
distinct phenomenal features.

00:59:40.770 --> 00:59:43.030
At the same time, the
inferences that some people want

00:59:43.030 --> 00:59:45.320
to make that they show that
consciousness transcends

00:59:45.320 --> 00:59:48.360
the brain, I don't think
a careful examination

00:59:48.360 --> 00:59:51.450
of the near-death experience
literature supports that.

00:59:51.450 --> 00:59:52.560
It might some day.

00:59:52.560 --> 00:59:54.340
I'm not saying that
it couldn't possibly.

00:59:54.340 --> 00:59:57.559
But I don't think
it's the case now.

00:59:57.559 --> 00:59:59.350
I think the most
important thing about them

00:59:59.350 --> 01:00:03.730
is that they might tell
us something about what

01:00:03.730 --> 01:00:08.520
people under certain conditions
experience when they're dying,

01:00:08.520 --> 01:00:10.820
or when they perceive
themselves to be dying.

01:00:10.820 --> 01:00:13.650
And that's very important
information for us

01:00:13.650 --> 01:00:19.750
to have for what I was
just talking about,

01:00:19.750 --> 01:00:26.610
for thinking about how we should
face an experience like that,

01:00:26.610 --> 01:00:28.640
that we're all in some
way going to have.

01:00:29.140 --> 01:00:33.140
Maybe that when we die, we don't
have a near-death experience

01:00:33.140 --> 01:00:33.980
in that exact sense.

01:00:33.980 --> 01:00:36.410
But the idea that
all of us are going

01:00:36.410 --> 01:00:39.180
to suffer from cardiac
arrest eventually,

01:00:39.180 --> 01:00:41.370
and that that's
something that we

01:00:41.370 --> 01:00:44.780
want to be prepared
